{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644072"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:01:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:01:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18033"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18033"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75811"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10747"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61324"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1337"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25075"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25082"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75811"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice with a six-month history of intermittent pain, numbness, and weakness in her right arm. The symptoms are exacerbated by overhead activities and improve with rest. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a positive Adson\u0027s test on the right side, and a bruit is heard over the right supraclavicular fossa.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is a potential cause of her symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cervical rib","Carpal tunnel syndrome","Rotator cuff tear","Cubital tunnel syndrome","Frozen shoulder"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings are suggestive of thoracic outlet syndrome, which is caused by compression of the neurovascular structures as they pass through the thoracic outlet. A \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical rib\u003C/strong\u003E is an anatomical anomaly that can contribute to this compression, leading to symptoms such as pain, numbness, and weakness in the affected arm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E involves compression of the median nerve at the wrist, leading to numbness and tingling in the hand. It does not cause symptoms in the entire arm or involve a positive Adson\u0027s test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erotator cuff tear\u003C/strong\u003E would cause weakness and shoulder pain with arm elevation, but numbness or a bruit over the supraclavicular fossa will not be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECubital tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E involves compression of the ulnar nerve at the elbow, leading to numbness and tingling in the ring and little fingers, but it does not cause symptoms in the entire arm or a positive Adson\u0027s test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrozen shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by stiffness and pain in the shoulder joint, but it does not cause numbness or weakness in the arm or a positive Adson\u0027s test.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thoracic outlet syndrome can be caused by anatomical abnormalities such as a cervical rib.","Compression of the neurovascular structures in the thoracic outlet can lead to symptoms of pain, numbness, and weakness in the upper limb.","Diagnosis of thoracic outlet syndrome involves clinical examination and imaging studies to identify structural causes."],"references":["Fehrenbach, M. J., \u0026 Herring, S. W. (2015). Illustrated Anatomy of the Head and Neck-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, et al. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534836/","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Henry BM, Vikse J, Sanna B, Taterra D, Gomulska M, P\u0119kala PA, Tubbs RS, Tomaszewski KA. Cervical Rib Prevalence and its Association with Thoracic Outlet Syndrome: A Meta-Analysis of 141 Studies with Surgical Considerations. World Neurosurg. 2018 Feb;110:e965-e978. doi: 10.1016/j.wneu.2017.11.148. Epub 2017 Dec 2. PMID: 29203316.","Chang KZ, Likes K, Davis K, Demos J, Freischlag JA. The significance of cervical ribs in thoracic outlet syndrome. J Vasc Surg. 2013 Mar;57(3):771-5. doi: 10.1016/j.jvs.2012.08.110. PMID: 23446121."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61324"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18033"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61324"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T15:33:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T15:33:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10747"}},"content":{"data":{"typ